{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c24a1568-1020-45d3-b164-e2225377f94f","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\npublic partial class App : Application\n{\n    public App()\n    {\n        InitializeComponent();\n    }\n\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    {\n        var window = new Window(new AppShell());\n\n        window.Created   += (s, e) => Log(\"Created\");\n        window.Activated += (s, e) => Log(\"Activated\");\n        window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Log(\"Deactivated\");\n        window.Stopped   += (s, e) => Log(\"Stopped\");\n        window.Resumed   += (s, e) => Log(\"Resumed\");\n        window.Destroying += (s, e) => Log(\"Destroying\");\n        // Visible on iOS/Mac Catalyst & Windows only\n        window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Log(\"Backgrounding\");\n\n        return window;\n    }\n\n    static void Log(string evt)\n        => System.Diagnostics.Debug.WriteLine($\"[Window] {evt} @ {DateTime.Now:T}\");\n}\n```\n\n**Typical transition order:**\n\n| Action | Events fired |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created → Activated` |\n| User switches away | `Deactivated → Stopped` |\n| User returns | `Resumed → Activated` |\n| App closed | `Destroying` |\n\n> **Tip:** On iOS/macOS, `Backgrounding` fires between `Deactivated` and `Stopped` — use it to save state via `e.State`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"92709379-8041-4032-90b9-f43d9d43cd24","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for debugging/logging purposes. This is a general programming knowledge question - I can answer it directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":466,"requestId":"D44A:298C73:1D96B9A:2127B93:6A07C195"},"id":"15201eab-c4d0-4ce0-bed4-e0afe3ad8ba0","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:00:15.829Z","parentId":"c9edc684-912a-46